entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 23 at 6:18PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
A broad tropical disturbance, Joint Typhoon Warning Center (JTWC)'s Invest 92W, is currently centered just west of Yap and north- northeast of Palau near 10.1N 135.5E, and is generating widespread heavy showers and gusty winds across the region. 92W is currently the subject of a Tropical Cyclone Formation Alert (TCFA), meaning it is expected to develop into a significant tropical cyclone (Tropical Depression) within the next 24 hours. Some models indicate the system could strengthen even more rapidly.
This afternoon's scatterometry analysis and surface observations for Palau reveal west-northwest surface winds of around 15 to 20 knots with gusts to 25 knots, with lighter winds of around 10 to 15 knots near Yap. Himawari visible satellite imagery shows widespread showers along the system's north and western flanks, covering Palau this afternoon. Model guidance indicates 92W will make a slight dip to the west-southwest as it passes just north of Palau tonight through Wednesday, strengthening slightly as it does so. This will lead to an increase in sustained winds and gusts through tomorrow night with winds expected to sustain above 22 knots over Palau coastal waters, generating seas hazardous to small craft, and a Small Craft Advisory has been issued. Gusts are expected to exceed gale force (34 knots) at times. Model ensembles show the potential for 3 to 6 inches of rainfall through Thursday, which could lead to an elevated threat for landslides, especially if soils become saturated from previous heavy rainfall.
Additionally, elevated north and west swells strengthened by 92W's passage are expected to generate hazardous surf of 9 ft along north and west reefs of Palau and west reefs of Yap beginning early Wednesday morning. Hazardous surf looks to spread to south facing reefs of Yap due to an elevated southwesterly swell behind 92W. The potential for hazardous surf will linger even after 92W exits to the northwest, as a monsoon pattern looks to set up in its wake, which could maintain elevated southwest swell, and potentially bring hazardous surf to south facing reefs of Palau later this week.
Residents and mariners should monitor the latest forecasts for the region at weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts and any information shared by WSO Palau and WSO Yap for their local regions, as well as JTWC bulletins under WTPN21 PGTW.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Yap; Melekeok; Airai; Koror; Peleliu; Angaur

entry.title: Flood Watch issued September 23 at 12:02AM AKDT until September 23 at 4:00AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
Scattered showers are moving into the panhandle tonight so periods of brief moderate to heavy rainfall are still possible. One item of concern is the potential to see training convective showers across mountains from moist south-southwest flow, driving higher than expected rainfall.
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be possible.
* WHERE...The following area, central Inner Channels. This includes the city of Juneau.
* WHEN...Until 4 AM AKDT Tuesday.
* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, other low-lying areas, and flood-prone locations. Creeks and streams may rise out of their banks. Low-water crossings may be flooded.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - A strong system moved through the area Monday afternoon and it brought moderate to heavy rainfall and strong winds. This resulted in continued risk for elevated streams and the potential for minor flooding. Widespread heavy rainfall is not expected due to the nature of the scattered rain showers. So widespread rainfall totals of less than a half inch are expected tonight, but higher amounts possible in isolated areas and at elevation.
entry.cap:areaDesc: City and Borough of Juneau

entry.title: High Surf Advisory issued September 23 at 5:26PM ChST until September 26 at 6:00AM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Large breaking waves of 7 to 9 ft.
* WHERE...North and west facing reefs of Palau and Yap, west and south facing reefs of Yap.
* WHEN...From 4 AM Wednesday to 6 AM ChST Friday.
* IMPACTS...Dangerous swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach erosion.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...An increase in north and west swell, driven by the westerly passage of intensifying Invest 92W, will generate hazardous surf along north and west facing reefs of Palau and along west facing reefs of Yap starting early tomorrow morning. The highest seas and surf are anticipated to be Wednesday through Wednesday night as 92W passes just north of Palau. Hazardous seas will then spread along south facing reefs of Yap and potentially Palau due to a strengthening southwest swell in the wake of 92W, starting late Wednesday night as a monsoon pattern sets up. Late in the week through the weekend, an elevated north swell is expected to move through the region, emanating from distant Typhoon Neoguri. This will be closely monitored for any potential hazards to north facing reefs.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Yap; Melekeok; Airai; Koror; Peleliu; Angaur

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued September 22 at 1:06PM AKDT by NWS Anchorage AK
entry.summary:
A rapidly strengthening storm-force low will bring a prolonged period of strong, gusty winds as it moves across the Bering Sea through Wednesday. Expect south to southeasterly winds along the low's front, followed by a longer duration of westerly winds behind the front. Forecast wind speeds and timing:
- Central Aleutians (Adak and Atka): This afternoon through late tonight, south to southeasterly winds gusting up to 50 mph. Tuesday morning through Tuesday night, westerly winds gusting up to 70 mph. Winds peak Tuesday afternoon and slowly diminish through Wednesday morning.
- Eastern Aleutians (Nikolski, Unalaska, and Akutan): Late tonight through early Tuesday morning, south to southeasterly winds gusting up to 50 mph. Late Tuesday afternoon through Wednesday morning, westerly winds gusting up to 70 mph. Winds peak late Tuesday night/early Wednesday morning and slowly diminish through Wednesday evening.
- Southern Alaska Peninsula (False Pass, Cold Bay, King Cove): Tuesday morning, southeasterly winds gusting up to 50-60 mph. Wednesday morning through late Wednesday afternoon, westerly winds gusting up to 65 mph. Winds peak late Wednesday morning and diminish through Wednesday evening.
